# Fix false-positive pattern match against tool-result JSON envelopes

## Overview

The "ERROR: pattern matched: You've hit your limit" keeps firing as a false positive at the end of a task iteration. Root cause: `_parse_stream` in `src/rlx/executor/claude_executor.py` adds any unrecognized JSON event line to the `recent` deque, and pattern matching runs against `recent_text`. Many real stream-json events are not modelled (`user`, `system`, `tool_result`, etc.) and their raw JSON envelopes embed user/tool payload — including this very codebase's literal `"You've hit your limit"` strings from `src/rlx/config.py`, docs, and tests. When a task ends without a terminal signal (e.g. agent's last message did not include `<<<RLX:ALL_TASKS_DONE>>>`), `_finalize_exit` substring-matches the tool-result-bearing JSON line in `recent` and emits the spurious limit/error.

The fix is to only include truly non-JSON lines in `recent`. Genuine CLI errors (rate limits, login errors) come from the Claude CLI as plain non-JSON output (merged stderr), so they will still be matched. Stream-json envelopes — recognized or not — never go into `recent` anymore.

## Context

- Files involved:
  - `src/rlx/executor/claude_executor.py` — `_parse_stream` adds raw JSON lines to `recent` in the `parse_event(raw) is None` branch (around line 279); this is the source of the false positive.
  - `tests/test_executor.py` — has `test_pattern_in_assistant_content_not_matched`, `test_pattern_in_result_event_not_matched`, `test_recent_text_deque`; needs new coverage for unrecognized JSON event types.
  - `tests/test_processor.py` — runner-level tests already exist for pattern handling; no change expected.
- Related patterns:
  - `match_pattern` does case-insensitive substring matching against `recent_text` only (not `output`).
  - The `assistant`/`content_block_delta`/`content_block_start`/`message_stop`/`result` events route through `_handle_event` and are NOT added to `recent` — they only contribute to `output_parts`. The fix aligns the unrecognized branch with that existing behavior.
- Dependencies: none.

## Development Approach

- Testing approach: TDD — add a failing test that simulates an unrecognized event type carrying the pattern in nested payload, verify the existing code matches it, then change behavior so it does not match.
- Complete each task fully before moving to the next.
- CRITICAL: every task MUST include new/updated tests
- CRITICAL: all tests must pass before starting next task

